SIMPLE: turnsole
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Turnsole
<hw>Turn"sole`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>tournesol</ets>, It. <ets>tornasole</ets>; <ets>tornare</ets> to
turn (LL. <ets>tornare</ets>) + <ets>sole</ets> the sun, L.
<ets>sol</ets>. See <er>Turn</er>, <er>Solar</er>, <pos>a.</pos>, and
cf. <er>Heliotrope</er>.]</ety> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>turnsol</asp>.]</altsp> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd>
<def>A plant of the genus <gen>Heliotropium</gen>; heliotrope; -- so
named because its flowers are supposed to turn toward the sun.</def>
<sd>(b)</sd> <def>The sunflower.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>A kind of
spurge (<spn>Euphorbia Helioscopia</spn>).</def> <sd>(d)</sd> <def>The
euphorbiaceous plant <spn>Chrozophora tinctoria</spn>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Litmus.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A purple dye obtained from the
plant turnsole. See def. 1 <sd>(d)</sd>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Turnspit</ent>⟦br⟧
